For {= contractor =}+ contractors or service entities publicly operating in Dallas-Fort Worth / North Texas fiber optic, structured cabling, network cabling, low-voltage cabling, or telecom-infrastructure work, cover each of the {= evidence_facet =} evidence facets listed below under each of the {= source_role =} source roles by supplying a public source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL under each facet/source-role pair) that carries a concrete facet-scoped public finding.

The purpose is neutral source provenance about what the public web says a contractor does, where it operates, which settings it serves, and which formal or public traces are visible. Contractor recommendations, ranking, quote or pricing utility, contact discovery, installation methods, network design, code-compliance conclusions, and safety-adequacy conclusions are not task evidence.

Evidence facets:
- `dfw_presence_and_role`: public evidence that ties the contractor to Dallas-Fort Worth, North Texas, the DFW Metroplex, or specific DFW-area cities, together with a role such as contractor, installer, service provider, vendor, public-program vendor, or local specialty contractor.
- `fiber_cabling_or_low_voltage_capability`: public evidence for a concrete fiber optic, structured cabling, network cabling, low-voltage, or telecom-infrastructure capability, such as fiber installation, backbone cabling, splicing, termination, OTDR or certification testing, demarc extension, aerial or underground outside-plant work, telecom-room work, or comparable infrastructure work.
- `service_scope_or_setting`: public evidence for a served setting or service scope, such as commercial office, healthcare, industrial, municipal or public sector, school or campus, data center, residential, carrier or telecom, multi-site work, emergency repair, or comparable scope.
- `formal_support_or_public_trace`: public evidence for an exact contractor-specific formal support signal, formal-program wording, or public trace, such as BICSI/RCDD or standards-based work, Fluke testing or certification documentation, manufacturer installer / partner / warranty program wording, DIR or cooperative contract status, public bid / award / vendor role, association or certification membership, permit / registration / license signal, or comparable public formal claim.

Source roles:
- `contractor_controlled`: a page whose visible ownership, authorship, or channel identity ties it to the named contractor, such as the contractor's own site, official social or company profile, contractor-authored public page, or comparable controlled surface.
- `external_public_trace`: a different public source not visibly controlled by the contractor, such as a public agency record, issuer/program/association/manufacturer page, customer/project page, local/trade article, job or bid record, detailed trade profile, or comparable contractor-specific public record.

Contractors ought to be real specialty contractors or service entities in the fiber / structured-cabling / network-cabling / low-voltage / telecom-infrastructure ecosystem. Pure manufacturers, carriers, generic managed-service providers, AV-only installers, electricians with no cabling or fiber claim, directory categories, product families, and placeholder names do not count unless the public evidence establishes an in-scope contractor or service-provider role. Sources should be fully public, accessible, and usable; pure contact forms, quote/RFQ forms, login/search shells, ranking-only pages, selection-advice pages, and generic redirects are not enough. Multi-contractor directory, category, search, and listing pages count only when the cited page contains a clearly separated contractor-specific profile or record with exact visible content for the claimed facet and source role; generic category pages, thin listing cards, rating pages, contact-only profiles, broad professional-network pages, and generic business summaries are not contractor-specific evidence for capability, service-scope, or formal-trace findings. Directory/profile presence alone, ratings, stars, directory category membership, business-status badges, employee counts, generic service tags, and generic marketing phrases like "preferred partner" or "certified team" are not `formal_support_or_public_trace` evidence unless the page gives an exact formal trace tied to the contractor.

Requirements:
- The page must clearly identify the named contractor or service entity.
- The page should make its source role and facet-appropriate page role visible and contractor-specific. For `contractor_controlled`, it should communicate contractor control, authorship, or official-channel identity; for `external_public_trace`, it should communicate an external public-record, issuer/program, association, manufacturer, customer/project, detailed trade/profile, article, job/bid, or comparable non-contractor-controlled context. For `external_public_trace`, generic business profiles and professional-network pages are eligible for capability, service-scope, or formal-trace facets only when the page itself supplies exact facet-bearing text tied to the named contractor, not merely category labels, ratings, locations, employee counts, generic business summaries, or directory membership. For `dfw_presence_and_role`, it should expose local presence or role framing, such as a DFW/North Texas service-area statement, local office or city page, contractor-specific profile, public-program vendor page, local project/article context, or similar page-role signal. For `fiber_cabling_or_low_voltage_capability`, it should read as contractor-specific service, capability, project, detailed profile, or public-record evidence for the relevant technical work. For `service_scope_or_setting`, it should read as contractor-specific evidence for a served market, facility type, project setting, customer class, service scope, or public-sector context. For `formal_support_or_public_trace`, it should read as evidence for the exact contractor-specific formal or public trace, such as contractor-owned formal-claim wording on the `contractor_controlled` side, or issuer/program, public contract/vendor/bid/award, certification/association/partner/warranty, permit/registration/license, customer/project, or comparable public-record context on the `external_public_trace` side.
- The page must expose a focused finding clearly scoped to the named contractor, evidence facet, and source role. For `dfw_presence_and_role`, this means a local geography plus role signal. For `fiber_cabling_or_low_voltage_capability`, it means a concrete source-stated capability rather than a generic "technology services" phrase or bare directory category. For `service_scope_or_setting`, it means a source-stated setting or scope rather than an inferred customer type, star rating, or category tag. For `formal_support_or_public_trace`, it means the exact source wording and support posture of a contractor-specific credential, certification, standard, test/warranty program, named partner/program relationship, association/membership signal, public contract/vendor/bid/award posture, permit/registration/license signal, or comparable public record. `contractor_controlled` findings can preserve contractor-claim posture; `external_public_trace` findings need the external or public source's own contractor-specific trace, without concluding that the contractor is compliant, adequate, approved for a buyer's project, safe to use, or better than another contractor.
